
[1]ceremony

   CEREMONY, n.

   1. Outward rite; external form in religion.

   2. Forms of civility; rules established by custom for regulating social
   intercourse.

   3. Outward forms of state; the forms prescribed or established by order
   or custom, serving for the purpose of civility or magnificence, as in
   levees of princes, the reception of ambassadors, &c.

   Master of ceremonies, an officer who superintends the reception of
   ambassadors. A person who regulates the forms to be observed by the
   company or attendants on a public occasion.
